"""
üìò Inheritance in Java - Complete Guide
==================================================

1. What is Inheritance?
--------------------------------------------------
Inheritance allows one class (child/subclass) to acquire properties and behaviors of another class (parent/superclass).
It helps in reusability of code and establishes a parent-child relationship.

Example:
--------------------------------------------------
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Animal eats food.");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks.");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog dog = new Dog();
        dog.eat();   // Inherited from Animal
        dog.bark();  // Child‚Äôs own method
    }
}

Explanation:
1. 'Dog' inherits from 'Animal' using 'extends' keyword.
2. 'Dog' can access both its own and parent methods.
3. Promotes code reusability and logical hierarchy.
4. Supports polymorphism when parent reference holds child object.

--------------------------------------------------

2. Why Inheritance is Important (10 Pointers)
--------------------------------------------------
1. Promotes code reuse.
2. Reduces redundancy.
3. Supports hierarchical organization.
4. Enables method overriding.
5. Simplifies code maintenance.
6. Encourages modular design.
7. Facilitates extensibility.
8. Encourages DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle.
9. Helps achieve polymorphism.
10. Reduces overall code complexity.

--------------------------------------------------

3. Key Concepts of Inheritance
--------------------------------------------------

a) Parent (Super) Class
class Parent {
    void showParent() {
        System.out.println("This is the parent class.");
    }
}

b) Child (Sub) Class
class Child extends Parent {
    void showChild() {
        System.out.println("This is the child class.");
    }
}

Pointers:
1. Parent class provides base structure.
2. Child inherits features and adds its own.
3. Achieved using 'extends' keyword.

c) extends Keyword
Used to define inheritance relationship.
Example: class Child extends Parent {}

d) super Keyword
Used to call parent class methods/constructors.
Example shown later.

e) Method Overriding
When child redefines parent method with same signature.

f) Constructor Chaining
Parent constructor called before child constructor.

g) Upcasting
Parent reference holding child object.

Example:
Parent p = new Child();

--------------------------------------------------

4. Types of Inheritance in Java (with Examples)
--------------------------------------------------

A. Single Inheritance
--------------------------------------------------
class Vehicle {
    void start() { System.out.println("Vehicle starts."); }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    void drive() { System.out.println("Car drives."); }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car car = new Car();
        car.start();
        car.drive();
    }
}

Pointers:
1. One class inherits another.
2. Simplest form of inheritance.
3. Enables code reuse.
4. Forms base for other types.
5. Common in real-world systems.

--------------------------------------------------

B. Multilevel Inheritance
--------------------------------------------------
class Animal {
    void eat() { System.out.println("Eating..."); }
}
class Mammal extends Animal {
    void walk() { System.out.println("Walking..."); }
}
class Dog extends Mammal {
    void bark() { System.out.println("Barking..."); }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog d = new Dog();
        d.eat();
        d.walk();
        d.bark();
    }
}

Pointers:
1. Chain of inheritance (Animal ‚Üí Mammal ‚Üí Dog).
2. Shows hierarchy in multiple levels.
3. Parent of one can be child of another.

--------------------------------------------------

C. Hierarchical Inheritance
--------------------------------------------------
class Shape {
    void draw() { System.out.println("Drawing shape..."); }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
    void area() { System.out.println("Area of Circle"); }
}

class Rectangle extends Shape {
    void area() { System.out.println("Area of Rectangle"); }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Circle c = new Circle();
        Rectangle r = new Rectangle();
        c.draw();
        r.draw();
    }
}

Pointers:
1. Multiple subclasses share same parent.
2. Common behavior defined in parent.
3. Promotes reusability across children.

--------------------------------------------------

D. Multiple Inheritance (via Interfaces)
--------------------------------------------------
interface A {
    void methodA();
}
interface B {
    void methodB();
}
class C implements A, B {
    public void methodA() { System.out.println("Method A"); }
    public void methodB() { System.out.println("Method B"); }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        C obj = new C();
        obj.methodA();
        obj.methodB();
    }
}

Pointers:
1. Achieved using interfaces.
2. Avoids ambiguity.
3. Java disallows multiple class inheritance but allows multiple interfaces.

--------------------------------------------------

5. Constructor Chaining Example
--------------------------------------------------
class Parent {
    Parent() { System.out.println("Parent Constructor"); }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    Child() {
        super(); // calls Parent constructor
        System.out.println("Child Constructor");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        new Child();
    }
}

Output:
Parent Constructor
Child Constructor

Pointers:
1. Parent constructor executes first.
2. Ensures initialization order.
3. Maintains construction hierarchy.

--------------------------------------------------

6. Method Overriding in Inheritance
--------------------------------------------------
class Animal {
    void sound() { System.out.println("Animal makes sound."); }
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    void sound() { System.out.println("Dog barks."); }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Animal obj = new Dog();
        obj.sound();
    }
}

Pointers:
1. Same method name/signature.
2. Executes child's version.
3. Enables runtime polymorphism.
4. Marked using @Override.

--------------------------------------------------

7. The super Keyword in Inheritance
--------------------------------------------------
class Parent {
    int num = 100;
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Parent display()");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    int num = 200;
    void display() {
        super.display();
        System.out.println("Parent num: " + super.num);
        System.out.println("Child num: " + num);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Child c = new Child();
        c.display();
    }
}

Pointers:
1. super calls parent constructor.
2. Accesses parent fields/methods.
3. Resolves naming conflicts.
4. Must be first in constructor.
5. Cannot access grandparent directly.
6. Enhances reusability.
7. Allows partial overriding.
8. Common in polymorphism.
9. Improves clarity in hierarchy.
10. Ensures parent initialization.

--------------------------------------------------

8. Inheritance and Access Modifiers
--------------------------------------------------
| Modifier | Inherited? | Notes |
|-----------|-------------|--------|
| private | ‚ùå No | Hidden from subclass |
| default | ‚úÖ same package | Package-level inheritance |
| protected | ‚úÖ subclass | Accessible to subclass |
| public | ‚úÖ Yes | Fully accessible |

--------------------------------------------------

9. Advantages of Inheritance
--------------------------------------------------
1. Code reuse.
2. Reduces redundancy.
3. Enables polymorphism.
4. Simplifies maintenance.
5. Promotes modularity.
6. Encourages clean hierarchy.
7. Improves readability.
8. Enhances productivity.
9. Supports abstraction.
10. Easier to extend behavior.

--------------------------------------------------

10. Disadvantages of Inheritance
--------------------------------------------------
1. Tight coupling between classes.
2. Parent changes affect children.
3. Complex debugging.
4. Reduces encapsulation.
5. Misuse leads to fragile code.
6. Can reduce flexibility.
7. Hard to track dependencies.

--------------------------------------------------

11. IS-A vs HAS-A Relationship
--------------------------------------------------
| Type | Relationship | Example |
|------|--------------|----------|
| IS-A | Inheritance | Dog IS-A Animal |
| HAS-A | Composition | Car HAS-A Engine |

--------------------------------------------------

12. Final Keyword in Inheritance
--------------------------------------------------
Usage Types:
--------------------------------------------------
A) final class
final class Vehicle {}
// class Car extends Vehicle {} // ‚ùå Error

Pointers:
1. Prevents inheritance.
2. Used for security-sensitive classes.
3. Common in utility classes.

B) final method
class Parent {
    final void display() { System.out.println("Fixed behavior."); }
}
class Child extends Parent {
    // void display() {} // ‚ùå Error
}

Pointers:
1. Prevents overriding.
2. Used for fixed implementation.
3. Provides consistency.

C) final variable
final int SPEED = 100;

Pointers:
1. Declares constant.
2. Must be initialized once.
3. Value cannot change.

--------------------------------------------------

13. Real-World Example of Inheritance
--------------------------------------------------
class Employee {
    String name;
    double salary;

    void work() { System.out.println(name + " works."); }
}

class Manager extends Employee {
    void manage() { System.out.println(name + " manages the team."); }
}

class Developer extends Employee {
    void code() { System.out.println(name + " writes code."); }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Manager m = new Manager();
        m.name = "Alice";
        m.work();
        m.manage();

        Developer d = new Developer();
        d.name = "Bob";
        d.work();
        d.code();
    }
}

Explanation:
1. Employee is parent class.
2. Manager and Developer inherit from it.
3. Each subclass adds unique functionality.
4. Common attributes reused.

--------------------------------------------------

14. Rules for Inheritance in Java
--------------------------------------------------
1. Use extends to inherit a class.
2. Constructors are not inherited.
3. Private members are hidden.
4. Single inheritance for classes only.
5. Multiple inheritance allowed via interfaces.
6. Use super() in constructors.
7. Child can override non-final methods.
8. Static methods not overridden.
9. Parent reference can point to child.
10. Prefer composition for flexibility.

--------------------------------------------------

15. Difference Between Inheritance and Composition
--------------------------------------------------
| Feature | Inheritance | Composition |
|----------|--------------|--------------|
| Relationship | IS-A | HAS-A |
| Reuse | Through extension | Through delegation |
| Coupling | Tight | Loose |
| Flexibility | Low | High |
| Example | Dog extends Animal | Car has Engine |
| Preferred | When true hierarchy exists | For code flexibility |

==================================================
‚úÖ Summary:
- Inheritance provides code reusability and hierarchy.
- Enables polymorphism and method overriding.
- Achieved using 'extends' and 'implements'.
- Use wisely to avoid tight coupling.
==================================================
"""
